We are given sorted integer array and two integers k and x. We have to return k closest elements to x in the given array.

Please look at optimal solution

Algorithm (easiest solution):
Step 1: We use two pointers left and right. left will start at 0 and right will start at arr_length-1
Step 2: while right - left + 1 > k:
                then if | arr[left] - x | > | arr[right] - x| then left difference is greater so we move left towards right
                else right difference is greater then or equal to left so we move left
Step 3: Here We add the window elements to the list
Step 4: We return the list.

class Solution {
    public List<Integer> findClosestElements(int[] arr, int k, int x) {

        int left = 0;
        int right = arr.length - 1;

        while(right - left + 1 > k)
        {
            if(Math.abs(arr[left]-x) > Math.abs(arr[right]-x))
            {
                left++;
            }
            else right--;

        }

        List<Integer> result = new ArrayList<>();

        for(int i = left; i<=right; i++)
        {
            result.add(arr[i]);
        }
        
        return result;
    }
}

Time complexity : O(n - k) and space complexity is O(1)


Optimal solution:
For this we use two pointers with binary search.

Step 1: Left  =0,  right = array_length - k.  
        Why we are doing array-length - k is left and right are possible starting indexes so for right = array_left -1 may not always fit the window size of k.
Step 2: now loop starts at left and goes until right
          now calcualte mid , mid = left + (right - left)/2

          if x - arr[mid] > arr[mid + k] - x  in this case arr[mid] is left most element in the current window and arr[mid+k] is next element after the window
          so if left is greather difference then next element out of the window then we move right so left = mid +1
          else if left is smaller or equal we move left , so right = mid      in equal case we are moving left as problem prefers that

Step 3: we make window into the list with loops starting at left and going to left + k
Step 4: Return the list.

Solution:


class Solution {
    public List<Integer> findClosestElements(int[] arr, int k, int x) {

        int left = 0;
        int right = arr.length - k;

        while(left < right)
        {
            int mid = left + (right - left)/2;

            if(x - arr[mid] > arr[mid + k] - x)
            {
                left = mid + 1;
            }
            else right = mid;

        }

        List<Integer> result = new ArrayList<>();

        for(int i = left; i< left + k ; i++)
        {
            result.add(arr[i]);
        }
        
        return result;
    }
}
